{"/service/ndnp/txdn/batch_txdn_kestrel_ver01/data/sn85060004/00516994757/1937112401/0812.xml":{"full_text":"E\u2018? \u00a7\u20ac$\u00a5\u00a7A\u00a7%\u00a7I&|E\nCALLE E=123l\nInternational News Dispatches\nAppear Exclusively in The Light\nVCI.. LVII\u2014NO. 309.\n9 CHILDREN SAVED FROM BLAZING HOME\nW K v E 9 v B W W 0 OF\nAlbert S. Burleson Claimed by Death| RE\nFAMED TEXAN\nallCCUMBS\nIN AUSTIN\nFuneral Services Set for\nPostmaster General in\nWilson Cabinet.\nAUSTIN, Nov, 24.\u2014(\u00ae\u2014Albert\nSidney Burleson, 74, postmaster\ngeneral in the cabinet of President\nWoodrow Wilson, died at his home\nhere today, a victim \u2018of heart dis\nease.\nA native of Sain Marcos and mem\nber of a pionear American and\nTexas family, Burleson retired from\npublic .life when the second cabi\nnet, term expired and since had de\nvoted his time to administering his\nfarms and ranches.\nPrivate funeral services were\nplanned for this afternoon with the\nRev. James 8. Allen, rector of St.\n'I!)lavld's Episcopal church, officiat\ng.\nLAMENTED BY ALLRED\nThe former cabinet officer is sur\nvived by his widow, Mrs, Adele\nSteiner Burleson; three daughters,\nMrs, R. V. Negley of San Antonio,\nMrs. Charles Grimes of Dayton,\nOhio, and Mrs.\u201d Bryant Smith of\nAustin; two sisters, and six grand\nchildren,\nGovernor James V, Allred describ-\nALBERT S. BURLESON\nForfher cabinet officer dies.\ned Burleson\u2019s death as a \u201cdistinct\nloss to Texas and the nation\u2122 The\nfirst Texan appointed to a cabi\nnet position, the governor said he\nwas \u201cone of our truly great men.\u201d\nSince his retirement he had main\ntained an objective interest in na\ntional and state affairs, declining\nappointment to public office, in\ncluding a directorship with the Col\norado River authority tendered by\nGovernor Allred.\nSUPPORTER OF F. D. R.\nDescribed as an \u201cold school\u201d Dem\nocrat, he was, however, a warm\nsupporter of President Roosevelt\nand much of the new deal program.\nHe was a close friend of his fel\nlow cabinet member, Josephus Dan\nfels, now United States ambassa\ndor to Mexico, who frequently vis\nited in the Burleson home.\nBurleson attended Texas A. and\nM. college, received the bachelor of\narts degree from Baylor univer\nsity in 1881, and his law degree from\nthe University of Texas in 1884,\nAdmitted to the bar in 1885, he\nbecame assistant city attorney here,\nserving in that capacity until he\nbecame district attorney for Travis\nand Williamson counties. In 1898\nhe was elected to congress and serv\ned 16 years before President Wil\nson chose him for the cabinet po\nsition.\n\u2014_\u2014\u2014\nWoman Sentenced\n\nin Mann Act Case\nCAMDEN, N. J, Nov, 24\u2014(\u00ae\u2014\nJudge John Boyd Avis in United\nStates District court today sen\ntenced Mrs. Agnes Stein, 43, of At\nlantic City to seven years in federal\npenitentiary on vice charges.\nShe was given four years on her\nconviction of violating the Mann act\nby bringing her adopted daughter,\nPeggy, from Philadetiphia to At\nlantic City for immoral purposes.\nHer husband, Louis Stein, 45, was\ngiven a three-year suspended sen\ntence because of ill health, and\nLouise Fisher, Mrs. Stein\u2019s house\nkeeper, was sentenced to one year\nand seven months.\n\nEX-CONGRESSMAN DIES\nSPARTANBURG. S. C., Nov. 24\u2014\nUP\u00bb\u2014Former Representative Samuel]\nJ. Nichols, 53, died suddenly last\nnight in a hospital. He represented\nthe Fourth district in congress from\n1915 to 1821,\nPublished by The Light Publishing Company\nSan Antonio, Texas\nLEFT IN ROAD\nGEORGE HEYEN, 14, OF 128 CLIFF AVENUE.\nHit and run driver left injured on Pleasanton road.\nHIT-AUN VICTIN\nFGHTS FOR\nLIFE\nGeorge Heyen, 14, of 128 Cliff\navenue, Wednesday was fighting for\nlife at Robert B. Green Memorial\nhospital, the victim of a hit and\nrun driver who left him crushed\nbeside the highway near Harlandale,\nThe Youth's injuries had been\ndiagnosed as a fractured skull,\ncrushed right leg, lacerations undI\npossible internal injuries.\nYoung Heyen was on his way to\nvisit a friend, Walter Moser, who\nlives on Cross avenue in Harlandale,\nTuesday night, when he was struck\nby a car in the 1700 block of Pleas-\nanton road. 1\nHe said the car had only ome\nheadlight, and that he looked back\nin time to see it but could not avoid\nbeing struck. 1\nHe was knocked to the side of the\nroad and eventually his cries were\nheard by Dr. V. H. Fondren who\noperates a dog and cat hospital op-\nposite the scene of the accident.|\nDr. Fondren gave what aid was pos\nsible and called an ambulance,\nDeputy Sheriffs H, C. Boek and\nHerman Winkleman were unable to\nfind any clues at the scene.\nThe boy is the son of G. R. Heyen.\nHe is a student of the junior school\nat Harlandale and a member of the\nglee club.\nYoung Heyen's dog, \u201cBuddy,\u201d\nstayed beside the youth at the scene\nof the accident until help arrived,\nand could not be drawn away until\nhis master had been placed in an\nambulance,\n\u2014e\n'Mrs. Lewis K. Beck\non City\u2019s Payroll\nMrs. Lewis Krams Beck is per\nmanently on the city payroll in\ncharge of the Sunken Garden the\nater. Mayor C. K. Quin stated Wed\nnesday after it was revealed Mrs.|.\nKrams Beck had been receiving a\n$100 salary for several months,\nCecil Beck, her son, is an the\nhealth department payroll as a\nsanitation inspector at $100 a\nmonth,\n\u2014_\u2014,\u2014\n\n{Crop Control Bill\nj Draft Completed\nWASHINGTON, Nov, 24\u2014(#)\u2014\nThe house agriculture committee\ncompleted toflay the draft of a com\npulsory crop contro] bill for wheat,\ncotton, corn, todacco and rice.\nChairman Jones (Democrat,\nTexas) said he would introduce the\n{measure in the house this afternoon,\n|adding: \u201cI hope that debate on\n||the bill in the house may start\nMonday.\u201d\n\u2014\u2014\u2014e\n\n$152,000 Set Aside\nJr for Gulf Channel\nWASHINGTON, Nov. 24\u2014(INS)\n|The war department today allotted\n18152000 for maintenance dredging\nL\u2018to restore the channel from Aransas\nPass to Corpus Christi.\nSoAN ON.IO ._.-\u2014-l\nH\u2014E TR *G\u2019!'/\u00ab \\I;\u2018G H\nI =z 11107 I\n20| K/ 4\nWE%'Q\u2018QIII.A \u2018-A-\u201c\u2018{\\\\\\'\nMember of the Associated Press *\u2014A Constructive Force in the Community\nSuspect in Hond\nKilling Nabbed\nEAGLE PASS, Nov. 24-\u2014John\nParker, 22, negro, wanted in connec\ntion with the fatal stabbing of Roy\nEmbry, farmer, in a Hondo bar No\nvember 14, is being held by Mexi\ncan authorities in Piedras Negras.\nHe was arrested at El Saucita near\nPiedras Negras Monday shortly aft\ner American authorities had re\nquested aid from Mexican officials.\nEfforts were being made to have\nhim deported by Mexican immigra\ntion officers to avoid the more com\nplicated steps required in extradi\ntion,\n\n\u2018Move Made to Pry\nOut Wage-Hour Bill\nWASHINGTON, Nov, 24\nChairman Norton (Democrat, New\nJersey) announced today the house\nlabor committez had voted, 16 to\n4, to recommend placing adminis\n|tration of the pending wages and\nhours bill in the hands of the la\nbor department instead of an inde\npendent five-member board.\nMrs. Norton told newsmen this\n|action was agreed upon in an effort\nto eliminate \u201cthe most serious ob\njection\u201d to the legislation.\n\u2014_\u2014\u2014\n\nIngot Production\n\nDrops Two Points\nNEW YORK, Nov. 24 \u2014(\u00ae\u2014Steel\ningot productson this week was es\ntimated today by Iron Age at 33 per\ncent of capacity, two points lower\n'|than last week, but two points\nhigher than estimated by the|\nAmerican Iron and Steel Institute|\nearly in the week. l\n\u2014_\u2014\n\n|Houston Heights\nDry, Court Rules|\nAUSTIN, Nov. 24.\u2014(\u00ae\u2014The Su-|\npreme court held today that Hous-l\nton Heights, a large area of wet|\nHouston, was dry by virtue of a lo-|\ncal option election about a quarter\u00a7\nof a century ago.\nBoy=Girl Romance\nEnds With Burial\nCHICAGO, Nov. 24.\u2014(INS)\u2014A\n\u2018teen age love affair which turned\nto tragedy when the girl falsely told\nher lover she was to become a\nmother had ended today with the\nburia] yesterday of Warren Slanley,\n17.\nStanley committee suicide, leaving\nbehind a passionate love note for\nLoretta Harynek, 15, whom he De\nlieved was to be a mother, l\nThe girl said she thought the\n\u201clove lie\u201d would make him happy.\nl As the body was lowered to its\ngrave, Mrs. Estelle Stanley, mother\n{of the dead youth, sank to her knees\nin a faint. Loretta her pretty face\n'hidden by a dark veil, wept silently.\n!The boy's father, divorced from the\nmother, was not present.\ni Stanley was a student at Missouri\nMilitary academy. His father is\n|head of a cosmetic company. The\n\nWEDNESDAY, NOVEMBER 24, 1937.\naLUMP HELD\nARTIFIGIAL\nBY FORD\nAuto Magnate Says Business\nRecession Is \u2018Pause\nBefore Climb\u2019.\nDETROIT, Nov. 24 \u2014(\u00ae\u2014Henry\nFord, in an interview today, said\nthat the present business recession\nis \u201ctemporary and artificial.\u201d\n\u201cNo one,\u201d he said, \u201cneed look at\nnext year with any uncertainty. The\npresent slow-down is not a set-back;\nit's the pause before another climb.\nTwo things helped to bring it on just\nnow and one of them was the un\ncertainty of business regarding po\nlitical interference, but congress\nis taking care of that. The other\nwas the stock market fluctuation,\n\u201cEverybody knows the stock mar\nket has no permanent effect on\nbusiness, but it does have an effect\non the stat\u00e9 of mind of the Amer\nican business man who plays the\nmarket. He often mistakes his per\nsonal depression for a business de\npression. The stock market has no\nmore real effect on American busi\nness than the results of a dog race\nin California.\u201d\n\u201cUPSIDE DOWN\"\nA contributing factor to the pres\nent \u201cpause,\u201d Ford said, has been the\nfact that money too long bas been\na \u201cprincipal commodity of com\nmerce.\u201d\n\u201cMoney,\u201d he said, \u201chas become a\nbusiness in itself instead of an ad\njunct to business, Money is not\nwealth; wealth is what money buys.\nBut that has been turned upside\ndown. The present system has gotl\nus twisted into producing things mr\nbuy dellars with, when what we\nneed is a money system that will\nproduce dollars to buy goods with.\nUnder the present system the tail\nwags the dog. Money is just part of\nsociety\u2019s transportation system for\nmoving goods from man to man; it\nbreaks down so often that it is time\nour financial engineers developed a\nbetter model.\u201d\nThe present money system as ex\nemplified by those \u201cwho manipu\nlate it for profit,\u201d Ford said, is en\ntirely out of date, and is in large\nmeasure responsible for recurring\nbusiness recessions. \u201cIt is a system\nthat seeks to control labor; wants to\ncontrol government, finance, food,\nindustry and even the schools. It\nmanifests an avariciousness that\nwould control everything.\u201d\nHANDICAP CITED\nFord explained that he had no\novernight panacea for what he\ntermed the out-moded money sys\ntem. \u201cBut any system,\u201d he added,\u2018\n\u201cthat seeks profits alone is terribly\nhandicapped to begin with.\u201d\n\u201cHere is a nation that might be\nthe richest nation in the world when\nactually we haven't enough of any\nthing, because there is not enough\nproduction. The need is here; the\n.|ablmy to produce is here; the stop\n|page is in the system that puts\nprofit before production\u2014and that\n3 is the money system.\u201d\nThe solution, Ford said. lies in\n-|teaching the coming generation the\nreal purpose of money\nLORETTA HARYNEK\n\u201cI'l nmever marry again.\u201d\n!girl, who has stoutly maintained she\n|and Stanley were secretly wed, said\ntoday:\ni \u201cI'l pever marry again.*\nPAGTOR GETS\nLIFE FOR\nMURDER\n:rRev. C. E. Newton to Ask!\nNew Trial; Verdict\nComes Quickly.\nPITTSFIELD, Ill., Nov. 24\nThe Rev. C. E. Newton was convict\ned today of slaying a loyal church\nworker and the jury fixed his pun\nishment at life imprisonment.\nA verdict was reached in six hours\nand 52 minutes.\nThe Missouri country preacher\nhad pleaded he was the victim of\ncircumstances in the brutal ham\nmer-slaying last July of Mrs. Dennis\nKelly, 45-year-old mother of Paris,\nMo.\n\u201cI'm not surprised at the verdict\nbecause of prejudice in this case,\u201d\nsaid the sleepy-eyed pastor when his\nfate was declared long before dawn.\nNEW TRIAL ASKED\n\u201cT intend to ask for a new trial.\nI will carry this to a higher court if\nnecessary.\u201d\nThe 5l1-year-old minister con\nferred briefly with Defense Attor\nney Maetin Turner and was taken\nback to jail.\nCircuit Judge A. Clay Williams,\nindicated sentence would be pro\nnounced today.\nTurner declared \u201cthis man Is in\nnocent of any crime: I'm sure of\nthat in my own mind.\u201d\nMerrill Johnston, youthful state\u2019s\nREV. C. E. NEWTON\nGets life sentence\nattorney who read to the jury New\nton\u2019s purported \u201cconfession\u201d to slay- l\ning his former Sunday school teach\ner \u201cwith something, I think a ham\nmer\u201d the night of last July 12, said:\n\u201cI'm well satisfied with the de-\ncision,\u201d\n6 BALLOTS TAKEN j\nMyra Hanan, 37-year-old foster\ndaughter of the preacher and whom!\nhe implicated in the murder through\ntestimony in his own defense, did\nnot remain up far the jury\u2019s de-\ncision. She was a major prosecution\nwitness,\nOne juror commented that no one\nheld out for acquittal. Another said\nsix ballots were taken before the\npunishment was determined. The\njurors were qualified to assess the\ndeath penalty. l\u2018\n\u2014_\u2014\u2014\ns\nArab Terrorist Is\nI\nSentenced to Hang\nJERUSALEM, Nov. 24\u2014(P\u2014The\nfirst of the Holy Land's new court-\nmartials dealt a warning to terror\nists today when it sentepced Sheik\nFarhan Saadi to be hanged for pos\nsessing firearms and ammunition, 1\nThe six-foot Arab, described as|,\none of Palestine\u2019s worst trouble|,\nmakers, was captured in a wheat|,\nbin near Jenin on Monday.\n_\n\nG-Man Aid Asked in\nLabor Death Probe\nMINNEAPOLIS, Nov. 24\nGovernor Elmer A. Benson today\nasked Attorney General Homer B.\nCummings to assign department of\njustice agents to aid in the solution\n|of the Patrick J. Corcoran assas\n|sination as William Mauseth, C. I\n|0. labor leader, reported to the po-\n|lice he was ordered \u201cto get out of\n|[town or eise you will get it\",\n\u2014_\u2014 e\nJUDGE TOWNER DIES,\nCORNING, lowa, Nov. 24\n!i.ludge Horace Mann Towner, ~2.\nformer governor of Puerto Rico and\nlformer Iowa congressman, died at|\nhis home here last night,\nEIGHTEEN PAGES\nELVIRA CISNEROS WITH \u201cWIMPY,\u201d HERO OF FIRE.\nFamily cat yowled, scratched until family waked, escaped\n-_\u2014 et\n1\nWeather Talking\n\nurkey ow\nSanta Claus got that letter about\nthe Thanksgiving football wmthrr!\u2018\nWinter was receding from San\nAntonio swiftly Wednesday in favor\nof the traditional Thanksgiving gob\nbler and the football games.\nJ. H. Jarboe took nothing short of\na personal pride in the turn of\nevents as he announced tempera\ntures will be somewhat warmer and\nThanksgiving will be bright and\nsunny with only occasional clouds.\nTemperatures were to go up to 54\ndegrees Wednesday, and the lowest\ntemperature Wednesday night will\nbe 35 degrees; three points above\nfreezing.\nMercury will climb up to 60 de\n|grees Thursday.\nThe lowest temperature Wednes\n|day morning was 30 degrees, This\n|low also brought a heavy frost\nwhich gave some parts of the city\nalmost the appeurance of a snew\nscape.\n\\f Today's maximum temperature of\n41 degrees was the lowest 24-hour}\n|maximum recorded here since the\ndead of last winter.\n\n'Sex Killer Faces\n1' Death Sentence\nNEW YORK, Nov. 24 \u2014(INS)\u2014\nSimon Elmore, 57-year-old former\nWPA worker found guilty of first\ndegree murder last night in the sex\nslaying of 4-year-old Joan Kuleba\non Staten Island. today faced a\nmandatory sentence of death in the\nelectric chair. The jury, which de-|\n|bated 71-2 hours, made no recom-\nmendation for mercy.\n\nCOLLEGE INAUGURAL\nHUNTSVILLE, Nov. 24.\u2014(INS)\u2014\n|Dr. Charles N. Shaver, former stu\n'|dent and graduate of Sam Houston\n|State Teachers college, today was\n'|officially inaugurated as its presi\ndent.\nAnnouncement\nEffective Monday, Nov. 29, The San Antonio\nLight's monthly subscription price will be 80\ncents. This adjustment in selling price\u2014an ad\njustment that scores of other newspapers\nthroughout the country have already been\nforced to make\u2014is occasioned by steadily rising\nnewsprint, labor, material and tax costs.\nThe increase will be shared with the earrier\nwho delivers this paper. The reader will be com\npensated by getting even a better newspaper,\nwith continued improvement.\nTHREE CENTS Per_copy in the city and_vicinity.\nTHREE CENTS Gits 'on \u2018trains and elsewhere.\nMAGS ARRESTS\nHORPLOTOUE\nIN FRANGE\nPARIS, Nov. 24\u2014(\"\u2014Surete na\ntionale officials promised mass ar\nresic today as the government an\nnounced it had broken a conspira\ncy to turn France Into a dictator\nship under a king.\nSurete operatives searched the\napartment of retired Aviation Gen\nera: Edouard Duseigneur, who pre\nviciely had been questioned con\ncerning activities of Les Cagoulards\n(*\u201cThe Hooded Ones\u201d). Les Cagou\n|lards are suspected of connection\n|witn a royalist revolutionary com\nmitiee for a civil war to overthrow\nFrence's republic.\nDuseigneur, accused by Communa\nists of heading the \u201cHooded Ones.\u201d\nwes interrogated again on ramifica\ntions of the organization while\nagents ranged the length of the na\ntion in search of \u201chigher ups\u201d of\nthe plot.\nAll government police units were\nco-operating in the nation-wide\ndrive to ferret out arms caches of\nthe conspirators, to discoverr their\nleaders and to learn the sources of\nfunds for vast purchases of arms.\nThe people\u2019s front regime declar\ned it was \u201ccapable of subduing all\ncriminal action directed against the\nrenublic,\u201d and ordered the surete to\nuse its ful] resources to crush revo\nlutionary activity,\n\u2014_\u2014\u2014\nReport Queen Marie\n\nCondition Better\nBUCHAREST, Nov. 24 \u2014(\u00ae\u2014The\ncondition of dowager Queen Marie\nof Rumania was reported consider\nably improved today.\n,4;///?/% 2 T T\nb TN\n2 B 1] Bt e\n4 IO/ S\nWIDOW, GIAL\nHURL TOTS\nTHROUGH\nWINDOW\nOne Child Cut by Glass\nin Duplex Rescue\non Barrera.\nBattling fast-spreading flames\nthat had cut them off from the\ndoorways, a widowed mother and a\nneighbor girl Wednesday saved the\nlives of five children in a fire that\ndestroyed a duplex at 620 Barrera\nstreet.\nMeanwhile, a big yellow tomeat\nnamed \u201cWimpy,\u201d was the uncon\nscious if disconcerted co-hero\nin the miraculous delivery.\nAt 5 a. m. Wednesday morning\nMrs. Josefena Cisneros was awak\nened by a 9-year-old son, Armando,\nwho said he heard \u201cWimpy\"\u201d mak\ning funny noises in the kitchen.\nMrs. Cisneros said she told the\nchild to go back to sleep, and dozed\nagain herself.\nA little later the child awakened\nher again and said he heard Wim\npy \u201ccutting up\u201d in the next room,\nAROUSES NEIGHBORS.\nMrs. Cisneros got up from the\nbed and opened the door to the\nkitchen. A wall of flame greeted\nher. Screaming to the four other\nchildren sleeping in the bedroom\nto awaken, she rushed to the ad\njoining apartment and aroused the\nfamily living there,\nThe adjoining apartment was oe\n|cupied by Luis Lozano, his two\nsons, Luis Jr., 23, and Noe, 20, and\n\u201c|a daughter, Margerite, 22. While\nthe elder Lozano, barefoot, ran to\nthe nearest firebox, Margerite sped\nacross the passage to aid in evacu\nating he Cisneros children.\nBesides the child, Armando. they\nare Elvira, 15; Elida, 11; Estella, 7,\nand Orlando, 3.\nBy the time the mother and her\nassistant were able to bundle the\nchildren up and seek an exit all\ndoors were blocked. With flames\nsweeping upon them, they broke\nthrough the windows and hurled\nthe children to safety, before leap=\ning themselves,\nCHILD CUT BY GLASS.\nThe youngest child, Orlando, was\ncut by glass from the broken pane,\nThe fire, estimated to have caus\n-|ed damage of $2500, completely gut\n.|ted the house, but left one closet\npartially intact in the Cisneros\napartment.\nWhen firemen had extinguished\n\"|the blaze they opened the door,\nWimpy darted out as if propelled\nfrom a gun. Bebe, the family dog,\n|escaped the blaze during early\nstages.\nPiremen said rapid spread of the\nflames and their enveloping nature\nmade the escape of the entire 10\npeople a miracle,\nMrs. Cisneros, home owner, said\ninsurance had only recently lapsed.\n\"The Lozano family lost all their\npossessions in the blaze.\n\u2014_\u2014\nThe Weather\nSan Antonio and vicinity: Gene\nerally fair and somewhat warmer\n\u2018Wednesday night. Thursday, partly\ncloudy and warmer.\nHighest temperature Wednesday,\nabout 54 degrees; lowest tempera\nture Wednesday night, about 35 de\ngrees; highest temperature Thurs\ni day, about 60 degrees; highest tem\nperature Tuesday, 41 degrees; low\nest temperature Wednesday morn\ning, 30 degrees. Light to moderate\nnortheasterly to easterly winds.\nEast Texas (east one-hundredth\nmeridian) Generally fair and some\nwhat warmer Wednesday night.\nThursday partly cloudy and warmer,\nModerate northerly to easterly winds\non the coast.\nWest Texas (west one-hundredth\nmeridian) Partly cloudy and warm\ner Wednesday night. Thursday,\npartly cloudy and warmer in south\neast portion.\nTEMPERATURES.\nl TUESDAY\u2014 2 A Maoses.s.33\n3 P Muveee..4l 3 2 M.ve,...32\n4 p Mm...e...40 4 a M.ii44..31\n|'5p m..l0038 5 a m.......30\n6 p. M.veees.38 6 a M.ieee..30\n1T P Moeeeee.3T 7 Miseees.3T\nE P Mounonseo37T S 8 Museses .34\n|9 p Movieee.36 9 a M.ovss...36\n10 p. m.......36 10 a m_.......41\n111 p. m.......35 11 a mM........49\n'12 p. m........35 12 NOOM .see...5L\nWEDNESDAY\u2014 1 p. m........52\n1a m.......34 2p m.......53\nWind. at 12:30 p. m.. 3 miles per\nhour from the southeast. Humidity,\nat 634 a m. 53 per cent: mean for\nNovember. S0 per cent: at 12:34 p. m,\n;53 per cent; mean, 33,\ni (Additional Weather ox Page 2).\nX","height":"21060","width":"16496"}}
